Dialogs.Dialog: Anegasaki
Hey, do you pour sauce over curry rice?
I've heard it occasionally...Is there someone like that?
Yes... a bit strange.
I wonder if it will give off a sweet taste, it depends on the person. Some people say sashimi and mayonnaise.
That might not be surprising. After all, you see, it's like a carpaccio, right?
Carpaccio... is it French food?
Italian cuisine. Beef is the basics, but there are also a lot of sashimi.
Do you eat it with mayonnaise?
Mayonnaise sauce. So, mayonnaise itself might go well with sashimi.
●He...soy sauce is good for sashimi.
Hehe, me too.
It seems that curry rice and sauce were common in the past.
Anegasaki
Is that so? How long ago was it in the past?
Huh, how was it? Are you more familiar with ▲Anegasaki*▲ like this?
Is that what I mean by aunt?
There's only one difference! See, it's from an old movie.
Movie...By the way...I think it's like the meal scene in "Graveyard on Third Street" was poured over curry sauce?
That kind of movie?
It was probably about 40 years ago.
See, I really know about the past.
I wonder if that's really praised.
Anegasaki
The curry and sauce may not be that surprising. There's even coffee in the frappe.
Frappe...shaved ice and coffee? Will the ice melt?
It's not hot, it's made into syrup...you know now.
It's like iced coffee is frozen. If it's shaved ice, how many ● should I pour it?
Hehe, all kids love strawberry syrup, right?
yes? So, I guess I'd get an adult if I pour soy sauce on it.
Frappe and soy sauce? Hehe.
Is it a sauce?
Hehe, already.
I mentioned shaved ice before, but what syrup does ▲Anegasaki*▲ like?
Anegasaki
Hehe, what do you think? It's not strawberries, right?
Lemon, melon, green apple, grapefruit, pine, blueberries, Uji tea... what else happened?
Why don't you shoot a few? It's a shame, but they're all wrong.
Orange, ramune...I've all said that it's both general and minor. Suspend.
condensed milk.
Oh, I forgot! But, that's...
What, you look dissatisfied?
Isn't it more childish than strawberries?
Hehe, I like it.
Anegasaki
There are animal protective colours, right?
Ah, I'm trying to blend in with the environment.
What about pandas?
Panda...
What did the black and white pattern look like?
What are white and black? Is there a place like that? Oh, the zebras are black and white too.
That striped pattern is a protective color between trees.
So, pandas too?
I don't think it's that way because it's not striped.
So, what is it?
Anegasaki
I came up with something similar to the panda pattern.
Oh, what does that black and white look like?
Rice balls.
A rice ball with seaweed only on the bottom. You know the standard type of convenience store.
...I understand that though.
Panda doesn't look like a rice ball from afar?
But if it's a rice ball, it's even more like you'll be targeted by other animals...it's just food.
If they were to aim for it, they probably wouldn't eat rice balls because they were carnivorous animals.
Pandas only exist in China, and rice balls are Japanese... I'm starting to get confused.
Anegasaki
I came up with something that resembles the panda pattern.
Other than rice balls?
Yes, police car.
mother. What's going on now?
Even poachers wouldn't get close to police cars.
Um, is Chinese police cars a black and white two-tone?
I don't know that much though.
Isn't the research too lenient? Fail, what?
Eh.
Anegasaki
There's a horror film called "Forty-seven Pandas, Cursed Slayer."
Of course it's not yet released.
I understand well. In that movie, pandas march through the snow...
It must be a scene of a raid.
yes. The white part of the panda is united with the snow, and the black part is thought to be just a shadow...no one notices it.
That theory is more convincing than rice balls and police cars.
Yeah. I think black and white is such a protective colour. The movie is also useful.
Yes, that's helpful. By the way, where will the panda be fired?
The Shinsengumi.
(...That movie is not helpful after all.)
Anegasaki
Hey, why are you a "green shop?"
What is it... what does it mean?
I wonder if a "vegetable shop" or "fruit shop" is no good.
Fish is a "fish shop" and meat is a "butcher". Only the greengrocer... why?
Because there are 800 types? The number of vegetables and fruits.
In terms of numbers, there are quite a few fish too. It seems like meat can be counted though.
Beef, pork, chicken, and mutton... I think it's within the range that you can count even if you include horses and boars.
The other day I saw kangaroo meat at the supermarket.
Kangaroo? Are you going to eat it?
Apparently so.
Every animal must have equal lives... Still... a bit shocked.
Do you understand why you're called a "green shop" that I mentioned before?
Anegasaki
I was thinking about it. Vegetables have been popular with Japanese people since ancient times.
It's anywhere in the world...
Especially Japanese people! Because they are farming people.
Well... that's right.
The close contact between vegetables and people, the integration of life, and the inevitable desires of life are born...
...A desire?
I decided to turn that off, so I put the same number. It's like the New Year's Eve bell.
...Hyakue?
Isn't it eighty-something about earthly desires?
Hundred eight.
Huh?
(Are you misunderstood...)
Anegasaki
It's about the greengrocer.
It's not worldly desires.
That's fine now. I think it has more to do with the benefits of vegetables.
Effective...it looks like a hot spring.
Vitamin C, Vitamin A... there are 100 benefits like these nutrients and diet effects.
So, "green shop"?
yes.
...Is that so?
Anegasaki
It's about a greengrocer.
Ah, the origin of the name?
I think it comes from the eight million people.
...Is it the number of gods?
yes. In short, there are many.
Hmm, that's what it is. Will you be doing some research and checking the answer soon?
It's fine, but... that's boring.
Is that what it is?
That's what it is. It's fun to think about things together.
Anegasaki
Towano City has become a sister city.
I've heard of which country it was, in Europe...
Why are they called "sister cities"?
Is it because we're close after all?
If that's the case, it would be fine to have a best friend city.
Because cities are similar? Area, environment, and eco-friendly measures.
That might be possible. But why are they "sisters"?
What does that mean?
Why aren't they brothers?
...I wonder why. Seven wonders of the world?
Hehe, what do you think?
Anegasaki
That's right, it's about the "sisters" of the sister city...
Ah, the Seven Wonders of the World.
It's not. I think the reason they are "sisters" is because they are more global standard.
standard?
See, world masterpieces aren't all "sisters."
Is that so?
Like "The Story of Hay."
Anything else?
Like illustrations of Nore Nore's sisters.
Hmm.
For this reason, "sisters" are the world standard.
(There are only two examples for the standard.)
I've said before that world masterpieces are all "sisters."
Anegasaki
Yeah.
What about "Fyodor's Brothers"?
Hehe, I'm getting mad. I looked it up.
Because I'm a library committee member.
But the brothers in the story aren't getting along well, they're heavy and gloomy.
Do you think cities and cities say, let's become like that kind of sibling?
...Maybe that isn't.
Wouldn't you be excited if you were invited to become a sister like "The Hay Tale"?
Certainly... is that a problem?
The name of the typhoon is a woman.
Anegasaki
What's the story?
A story about sister cities. Come to think of it, I think the typhoon was a woman too.
Ah, the name of the hurricane.
Susie and Katrina were angry ▲Anegasaki*▲.
There's no last one.
Haha, well, that's it. This kind of thing really suits women than men.
Maybe it's because you're a boy?
Is that so?
All boys like cute girls, right?
Well. ●I also like it.
Hmm...
▲Like Anegasaki*▲.
I'm an idiot now.
